Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.180 --> 00:00:04.090
Supply chain attacks
are one of the biggest threats you and

00:00:04.160 --> 00:00:07.760
me as developers, web developers,
can face these

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:11.560
days. They are becoming more frequent
and more serious.

00:00:11.610 --> 00:00:15.340
And I talked about that in another video,
which I released

00:00:15.380 --> 00:00:18.240
earlier this week on my other channel,
link below.

00:00:18.260 --> 00:00:22.000
Because this week,
when I'm recording this, there

00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:25.740
the Axios library. By the way,
in this video here, I'm

00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:29.540
focusing on the JavaScript ecosystem,
but supply chain

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:32.610
attacks are not exclusive to the
JavaScript ecosystem.

00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:35.960
They are just particularly popular.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:39.420
They are for various reasons,
but that's not the focus here.

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:43.340
Therefore, in this video here,
I'll share concrete

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:47.540
steps you can and probably should take,
and I'm taking, I'm

00:00:47.640 --> 00:00:51.560
doing,
to protect against supply chain attacks so

00:00:51.580 --> 00:00:55.480
the next time one happens,
you can keep on sleeping

00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:58.180
happily because you're not in danger.

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:01.980
By the way, if this is helpful,
check out academind.com.

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:06.020
There,
I have courses on all kinds of AI

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:08.520
related stuff, so
that might be interesting to you.

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:12.700
So,
what can you do to protect against supply

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:16.980
It's two main layers, so to

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:20.720
say. The first layer is that you want to

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:24.540
reduce the danger of being affected by
such an

00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:28.420
attack. The second layer is
that you want to

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:32.260
reduce the blast radius if you
are affected, and both

00:01:32.380 --> 00:01:36.060
are important because you can reduce the

00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:39.140
danger, but you can't reduce it to zero.

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:43.360
There is no 100% guarantee that

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:47.240
you will never be affected. So,
you can reduce it, but not to zero.

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:51.240
So, therefore, this second point,
if you are affected, you wanna

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:54.220
reduce the damage the attack can do.

00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:58.360
Now, each point he-
consists of a couple of steps you can

00:01:58.420 --> 00:02:01.920
ta- take,
a couple of things you should consider,

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:05.940
reducing the danger.
Maybe you already heard about

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:09.220
that. You want to set a minimum

00:02:09.340 --> 00:02:12.500
release, uh, age for any

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:16.590
packages you add to your project. Uh, what

00:02:16.620 --> 00:02:20.040
does this mean? It means if you are

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:23.900
using,
if you're working in a web dev project

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:28.120
using npm for managing your packages,
or bun or pnpm,

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:32.720
then some of these tools allow you to add
dedicated

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:36.660
settings that help you stay secure, so to

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:40.600
say. For example, if you are using bun,
not necessarily the bun

00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:44.380
API, not necessarily in your code,
but as a package manager, which you

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:48.299
can do instead of npm, then bun has a

00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:51.440
minimum release age setting you can add

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.920
in your bunfic.toml file, which
is simply a

00:02:55.960 --> 00:02:58.700
configuration file you can add to your
project.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:02.440
And if you add this setting here
and you're using bun for

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:06.260
managing your dependencies,
that's important of course,

00:03:06.300 --> 00:03:10.100
to only ever install dependencies that
are at least that

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:13.880
old. Or dependency versions, I should say,
that are at- at least

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:17.400
that old. So, that is three days in-
in seconds here.

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:22.060
So, that of course,
is a huge security step up because those

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:25.460
supply chain attacks in the past have
typically been

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:29.420
detected and remedied within a few hours.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:33.180
So, if you make sure
that you never install package versions

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:36.820
are younger than, let's say, three days,
you're already

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.780
pretty, pretty secure.
If you're using pnpm

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:44.800
as a package manager instead of bun
or npm, you have a similar

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:48.460
setting you can make. And if you are using

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:51.640
npm, good old npm,
you can actually also add a

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:55.580
.npmrc file in your project that

00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:59.500
configures how the npm package manager
works, so to

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:03.600
say. And in there, if your npm version,
I think,

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:07.620
is at least 11.11.1, you

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:11.380
can also add a min-release-age

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:16.440
setting and npm should honor that
and not install

00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:20.120
packages that are younger than
that date or package

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:23.920
versions. Important,
you really need to set this setting

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.740
this is null. The same for bun. So,
by default, no minimum

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:31.220
age is assumed. A sensible default that is

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:34.920
enforced by bun though is that by default,

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:38.960
it does not execute lifecycle scripts

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:42.050
of third-party packages. Now, what
is that?

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:45.980
Well, in your package.json file,
you of course typically have

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.240
scripts,
and you could also have scripts like

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:53.380
post-install scripts in there,
which libraries could add to

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:57.110
define some code
that should execute whenever

00:04:57.160 --> 00:05:01.080
installed, and that
is how many of those supply chain attacks

00:05:01.090 --> 00:05:04.000
They add malicious code as a post-install
script.

00:05:04.660 --> 00:05:07.550
Bun, by default, blocks those scripts.

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:11.200
So,
if you're using bun for package

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:14.880
another big security step up because those
malicious

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:18.740
scripts shouldn't get executed.
I'm saying shouldn't

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:22.710
because bun has a default list of trusted
dependencies,

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:26.580
which actually do have their scripts
executed, and you could

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:30.460
also manage your own list here.
And therefore, one

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.180
thing you might wanna do to override
that trusted dependencies

00:05:34.280 --> 00:05:37.860
list bun has is in your package.json

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:41.570
file, you can add that trustedDependencies

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:45.730
setting, which will be ignored by npm,
but which will be honored by

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:50.160
bun.
And if you set this to an empty array,

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:53.880
bun maintains to ensure
that no package has their

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:56.840
post-install and other lifecycle scripts
executed.

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:59.200
So, that's another security measure.

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:02.740
You wanna block those package scripts.

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:06.360
For npm, you can also get there. In the

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.780
.npmrc file, you can add a

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:12.840
ignore-scripts setting
and set this to true

00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:16.880
so that if you're using npm for package
management, you also don't execute

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.720
those, uh, lifecycle scripts. And then

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:24.680
there is a last point,
which I read about a lot, which

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:27.390
I think is a bit overhyped,
but still worth mentioning.

00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:30.370
You have that interesting

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:34.390
package.lock.json file or bun.lock file or

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:38.260
other lock files in your project,
depending on which package manager

00:06:38.340 --> 00:06:41.200
you're using. I have a bun.lock file,
for example.

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:45.740
These lock files get created automatically
normally when

00:06:45.820 --> 00:06:49.620
you install packages through npm,
then you get a package.lock

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:52.700
file, or through bun,
then you would get a bun.lock file.

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:56.920
Now, what these files do
is they lock in concrete,

00:06:57.240 --> 00:06:59.200
highly-specific package versions.

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:02.460
By default, in your package.json file,

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:06.372
uh-You might have dependencies like

00:07:07.112 --> 00:07:10.432
this, which says, "I want at

00:07:10.632 --> 00:07:13.652
least that version of the

00:07:14.172 --> 00:07:18.132
dependency," and major updates will not be
downloaded automatically, but

00:07:18.172 --> 00:07:19.802
patch updates, for example, would.

00:07:20.212 --> 00:07:22.952
So this does not mean
that I want exactly version

00:07:23.112 --> 00:07:27.052
2.1.10 for this package, but

00:07:27.072 --> 00:07:30.252
I want at least that version. And
that can be problematic.

00:07:30.712 --> 00:07:34.472
If version 11, for example,
would be effective, then I would

00:07:34.572 --> 00:07:38.492
download it if I
were to reinstall my dependencies, or,

00:07:38.552 --> 00:07:42.032
to push this to production and in the

00:07:42.072 --> 00:07:45.832
CI/CD process, I install my dependencies,
that might

00:07:45.872 --> 00:07:48.572
install a different version than I
was using locally.

00:07:49.152 --> 00:07:51.052
That is where the lock file comes in.

00:07:51.152 --> 00:07:53.892
It locks in specific versions,

00:07:54.412 --> 00:07:58.072
exactly the versions you installed
locally, and therefore the lock file

00:07:58.212 --> 00:08:02.002
should be committed to version control,
should be committed to GIT and

00:08:02.112 --> 00:08:06.032
GitHub, for example, so that
when you're deploying this, or if

00:08:06.092 --> 00:08:09.692
you were to delete your note modules
folder and you reinstall all

00:08:09.712 --> 00:08:12.672
dependencies, you download and install

00:08:12.772 --> 00:08:16.432
exactly the dependencies you were using

00:08:16.532 --> 00:08:20.392
locally. So exact,
specific dependency versions are

00:08:20.452 --> 00:08:24.332
being locked in here. And that
is also kind

00:08:24.392 --> 00:08:28.252
of a protection mechanism, of course,
because if you have safe versions

00:08:28.372 --> 00:08:32.032
locally or before,
and you now reinstall or

00:08:32.112 --> 00:08:36.072
install on another server based on the log
file, you get those

00:08:36.082 --> 00:08:37.462
safe versions again.

00:08:38.432 --> 00:08:42.232
Even beyond supply chain attacks, the

00:08:42.312 --> 00:08:46.012
log file is useful, of course,
because it ensures that

00:08:46.072 --> 00:08:49.982
app,
you're really installing exactly the same

00:08:50.012 --> 00:08:53.822
if some patch release of some dependency
you were using

00:08:53.912 --> 00:08:57.822
introduced a bug, for example,
you would not have that in the deployed

00:08:57.892 --> 00:09:00.272
version. So it's good for predictability.

00:09:01.092 --> 00:09:05.052
So that is important.
That reduces the danger of being affected

00:09:05.092 --> 00:09:08.872
you're not pulling in new versions early
and you're

00:09:08.912 --> 00:09:12.352
blocking those scripts. And with that,
you are already super,

00:09:12.612 --> 00:09:16.472
super safe. You could stop here
and it would be way better than what you

00:09:16.532 --> 00:09:20.202
probably had before,
but it's really important to me,

00:09:20.332 --> 00:09:24.322
100% safe. You have no guarantee that

00:09:24.652 --> 00:09:28.212
such attacks will be caught within a few
hours.

00:09:28.292 --> 00:09:31.932
It could take a week,
depending on how sophisticated an

00:09:31.992 --> 00:09:35.632
attack is,
depending on how popular a package is.

00:09:36.112 --> 00:09:39.052
You have no guarantee
that it will only be hours.

00:09:39.132 --> 00:09:42.752
So saying that you don't want to download
packages that

00:09:42.792 --> 00:09:46.212
aren't at least three days old,
package versions I mean,

00:09:46.832 --> 00:09:50.712
might not always be enough.
Blocking scripts also

00:09:50.792 --> 00:09:54.692
is not necessarily always enough because
that's just one popular

00:09:54.772 --> 00:09:58.412
way of launching such an attack, but,
of course, a more sophisticated

00:09:58.452 --> 00:10:02.152
attack could inject code into the actual
package code

00:10:02.432 --> 00:10:05.152
and that code could then execute on your
system.

00:10:05.301 --> 00:10:08.772
If you're building a server side
application, let's say, and you're

00:10:08.892 --> 00:10:12.652
downloading, let's say, Express.js,
and Express.js

00:10:12.752 --> 00:10:16.252
or some dependency of Express.js had
malicious code injected,

00:10:16.801 --> 00:10:20.752
that code might be executing on your
machine as you're running the

00:10:20.772 --> 00:10:22.312
development server, for example.

00:10:22.352 --> 00:10:26.301
So that is great,
but it's not a 100% protection.

00:10:26.792 --> 00:10:30.722
That is why we also want to reduce the
blast radius, which in general is a

00:10:30.752 --> 00:10:34.572
good idea, by the way,
because things can go wrong.

00:10:35.072 --> 00:10:38.872
So what do I mean by that? I, for example,
mean that you

00:10:38.932 --> 00:10:42.452
want to encrypt and hide your

00:10:42.612 --> 00:10:46.092
secrets. Now, what are secrets?
Secrets are

00:10:46.412 --> 00:10:49.932
stuff like my newsletter API key in the

00:10:49.972 --> 00:10:52.672
Academind.com website source code.

00:10:53.152 --> 00:10:56.012
Uh,
this is required for making newsletter

00:10:56.132 --> 00:10:59.832
By the way,
great idea to sign up there to be the

00:10:59.972 --> 00:11:03.752
sales, new courses, and stuff. And,
of course, that is not

00:11:03.812 --> 00:11:07.712
something I want other people to get
because they could use that to

00:11:08.672 --> 00:11:11.932
manipulate my newsletter contact list,
for example.

00:11:12.452 --> 00:11:16.192
So that is a secret. That secret,
that concrete

00:11:16.292 --> 00:11:20.152
key should not be stored in my code base
and should also not be

00:11:20.232 --> 00:11:23.792
in my dot env file. Now,
as web developers, we

00:11:23.872 --> 00:11:27.552
tend to put a lot of stuff in dot env,
and I admit I

00:11:27.732 --> 00:11:30.052
also do this in my courses because it's
convenient.

00:11:30.572 --> 00:11:34.552
But in theory, and not just in theory,
really, to be safe, that

00:11:34.572 --> 00:11:38.312
dot env file should not contain anything
you're not comfortable sharing.

00:11:38.772 --> 00:11:42.632
So I can freely share this file with you
because there's nothing in there

00:11:42.712 --> 00:11:46.232
that would matter to you or
that would be insecure to share, right?

00:11:46.792 --> 00:11:50.732
So that is what the s- the end goal should

00:11:50.792 --> 00:11:54.592
be. Naturally, the question then is, well,
where do you then put these

00:11:54.632 --> 00:11:56.522
values that you need during development?

00:11:56.662 --> 00:11:59.712
And the answer is you wanna use a service
like Doppler.

00:11:59.802 --> 00:12:02.492
And no, this video
is not sponsored by them.

00:12:02.932 --> 00:12:06.772
There also are alternatives,
like Inphysical, or you could build your

00:12:06.812 --> 00:12:10.492
own alternative, of course. These
are services that allow you to

00:12:10.632 --> 00:12:14.252
manage your secrets in the cloud
and pull them into your

00:12:14.372 --> 00:12:18.072
project,
inject them into the environment as you

00:12:18.112 --> 00:12:22.012
development or production server so
that they are, uh, fetched

00:12:22.312 --> 00:12:26.192
just in time, so to say. And you can,
for example, use

00:12:26.212 --> 00:12:27.432
Doppler for free.

00:12:28.332 --> 00:12:32.012
You can start and use it for free
if you have, like, a, a small

00:12:32.032 --> 00:12:34.832
scope just up to three users,
up to 10 projects, I think.

00:12:35.472 --> 00:12:39.192
So that can then be a great way of
protecting yourself.

00:12:39.312 --> 00:12:42.732
So I, for example,
set up a project here in Doppler for my

00:12:42.792 --> 00:12:46.392
website. In there,
you can have different environments,

00:12:46.492 --> 00:12:50.452
you can define various secrets,
store the secret values there, and

00:12:50.492 --> 00:12:54.292
then you can pull them in by reusing the
Doppler CLI, which you

00:12:54.332 --> 00:12:58.172
need to install.
And then you can run Doppler Run

00:12:58.272 --> 00:13:02.152
development server, and
that will inject those secrets just in

00:13:02.252 --> 00:13:06.193
time to make them available.So that
is how you can make

00:13:06.244 --> 00:13:10.004
sure that they're not lying around on your
system, in your project, or

00:13:10.044 --> 00:13:13.984
anywhere else, and therefore,
if you would be affected by any attack,

00:13:14.004 --> 00:13:17.944
doesn't matter,
but let's say a supply chain attack,

00:13:18.004 --> 00:13:21.664
just read your .env file
and find your secret

00:13:21.684 --> 00:13:24.684
values because the values aren't in
that file.

00:13:25.154 --> 00:13:28.524
And of course,
it's not just secrets you might be using

00:13:28.564 --> 00:13:32.084
Those supply chain attacks scanned your
entire machine.

00:13:32.104 --> 00:13:36.044
By the way, it also didn't matter
if you were using Windows or Linux

00:13:36.504 --> 00:13:40.264
those attacks work with all operating
systems and they were looking for all

00:13:40.344 --> 00:13:43.244
kinds of passwords
or keys you might have on your system.

00:13:43.624 --> 00:13:47.424
So outside of your project,
you don't just wanna hide or encrypt your

00:13:47.904 --> 00:13:51.864
secrets, you also wanna, of course,
encrypt any SSH

00:13:51.904 --> 00:13:53.924
keys you have lying around on your system.

00:13:54.144 --> 00:13:57.894
Use tools or services like 1Password for
managing your

00:13:58.024 --> 00:14:00.484
passwords and secrets on your system.

00:14:00.514 --> 00:14:03.404
And no,
they are also not sponsoring this video.

00:14:03.744 --> 00:14:07.494
I'm just using them personally. So that,
of course, are great ideas

00:14:07.564 --> 00:14:11.364
because if there is simply nothing
valuable

00:14:11.544 --> 00:14:15.004
lying around on your system, there
is nothing that

00:14:15.224 --> 00:14:19.184
could be stolen.
Another step up here would be to

00:14:19.304 --> 00:14:23.284
use a dedicated dev environment

00:14:24.004 --> 00:14:27.844
or machine for development.
So what do I mean by

00:14:27.884 --> 00:14:31.744
that?
I mean that you may be using your one

00:14:31.784 --> 00:14:35.584
PC for everything.
You do your banking business there,

00:14:35.624 --> 00:14:39.354
YouTube videos there,
you do all the personal stuff there,

00:14:39.364 --> 00:14:42.944
develop there. And of course,
there's nothing wrong with that, but

00:14:43.104 --> 00:14:46.964
have any way of doing your development
