kernel.
That's why a virtual machine might be

00:15:42.064 --> 00:15:45.504
But spinning up such a virtual machine
might be a good idea too.

00:15:45.684 --> 00:15:49.454
For example, I got Multipass installed
and I created, uh,

00:15:49.744 --> 00:15:53.244
a bunch of virtual machines there,
actually one base machine, which I keep on

00:15:53.284 --> 00:15:57.144
cloning because Multipass has a clone
command where you can use

00:15:57.244 --> 00:16:01.204
one base machine and clone to create a new
machine based on it, to use it as a base

00:16:01.264 --> 00:16:04.714
image essentially. And
if they're not running,

00:16:05.034 --> 00:16:08.684
So I only have my development machine
running and I have one development virtual

00:16:08.724 --> 00:16:11.224
machine per project in my case here.

00:16:11.244 --> 00:16:15.224
And then that project,
so this project you see here runs in that

00:16:15.284 --> 00:16:17.844
virtual machine. It runs in there.

00:16:17.964 --> 00:16:21.744
So if anything bad happens in there,
it happens in that virtual machine And

00:16:21.924 --> 00:16:25.594
in that machine, there
is nothing except for this

00:16:25.644 --> 00:16:29.324
project. Now, there
are a couple of gotchas here

00:16:29.384 --> 00:16:33.164
related to using AI tools like Claude Code

00:16:33.244 --> 00:16:37.074
in there or Git, because
if you want to be able to git push, for

00:16:37.144 --> 00:16:41.114
example,
you need to be able to connect your, your

00:16:41.144 --> 00:16:44.644
Git account here. So I need to ha-
to have my Git credentials

00:16:44.824 --> 00:16:48.464
somewhere in the virtual machine,
and those could be stolen if they were

00:16:48.564 --> 00:16:50.984
stored there. The same for Claude Code.

00:16:51.044 --> 00:16:54.484
If I do install Claude Code in
that machine or

00:16:54.604 --> 00:16:58.564
Codex or whatever,
and I then log in in there, my

00:16:58.764 --> 00:17:02.144
session token must be stored in
that virtual machine.

00:17:02.264 --> 00:17:03.894
Now,
there are a couple of workarounds though.

00:17:04.084 --> 00:17:07.704
For example,
I did register my virtual machine as a SSH

00:17:07.764 --> 00:17:11.734
host in my SSH config file on my system,

00:17:12.024 --> 00:17:15.604
and in there I set forward agent to yes.

00:17:16.064 --> 00:17:19.943
Now, what exactly does this do?
This ensures

00:17:20.004 --> 00:17:23.024
that I can actually add

00:17:23.844 --> 00:17:26.824
certain credentials to my

00:17:27.504 --> 00:17:31.044
SSH agent, to my SSH tool, so to say here,
and

00:17:31.484 --> 00:17:34.784
forwards them to the virtual machine.
I don't store them in there.

00:17:34.884 --> 00:17:38.564
I don't copy them in there, but
when I'm then connected to that virtual

00:17:38.624 --> 00:17:42.504
machine as I am here using VS Code remote

00:17:42.684 --> 00:17:46.644
feature where you can connect to a host
via SSH, in there,

00:17:47.204 --> 00:17:50.964
I then have various, uh, keys
or credentials

00:17:51.004 --> 00:17:54.464
available. Uh, this here, for example,
is my

00:17:54.684 --> 00:17:58.064
GitHub SSH key,
which I use for authenticating with GitHub

00:17:58.604 --> 00:18:02.544
That allows me to use git commands,
and for example,

00:18:02.724 --> 00:18:06.524
push or pull from inside my terminal in VS

00:18:06.564 --> 00:18:10.144
Code in that remote machine which
is connected via SSH using the

00:18:10.164 --> 00:18:12.444
credentials that are stored on my host
machine.

00:18:12.484 --> 00:18:16.404
So the credentials
are not copied in there, they

00:18:16.924 --> 00:18:20.184
So therefore,
I don't expose them in there.

00:18:20.264 --> 00:18:23.924
Of course,
if some process got access to my SSH

00:18:23.984 --> 00:18:27.794
session in there,
it could still access those credentials,

00:18:27.824 --> 00:18:30.224
security layer. That is the point.

00:18:30.264 --> 00:18:34.074
By the way, if stuff like that
is interesting to you

00:18:34.104 --> 00:18:38.064
that,
about SSH and how I forward credentials

00:18:38.084 --> 00:18:40.484
know in the comments
and I'll create a dedicated video on that.

00:18:41.144 --> 00:18:45.024
But that is one thing I'm doing. Now,
when it comes to AI agents like Claude

00:18:45.204 --> 00:18:48.864
and by the way,
I have an amazing Claude Code course,

00:18:48.964 --> 00:18:52.804
out,
or you get my subscription to get access

00:18:52.884 --> 00:18:56.444
side note.
If I wanna use Claude Code in there, I can

00:18:56.484 --> 00:19:00.344
install it and authenticate
and live with the fact that my

00:19:00.424 --> 00:19:04.104
session token is stored in there,
because if something bad would

00:19:04.224 --> 00:19:07.264
happen, I could always revoke

00:19:07.544 --> 00:19:11.104
my sessions from inside my

00:19:11.164 --> 00:19:14.354
Claude dashboard to, uh, kind of

00:19:14.784 --> 00:19:17.644
restrict the amount of damage
that can be done.

00:19:17.774 --> 00:19:21.704
And since it's a subscription,
an attacker can't do more than use up my

00:19:21.784 --> 00:19:25.484
overall subscription usage,
but they can't actually hurt me

00:19:25.564 --> 00:19:29.384
beyond that So I'm fine with that.
If I don't

00:19:29.444 --> 00:19:33.204
want that, I could also run Claude Code
or whatever on my host

00:19:33.264 --> 00:19:36.644
machine and just tell it to

00:19:36.684 --> 00:19:40.584
connect to that virtual machine via SSH
and run

00:19:40.624 --> 00:19:43.224
commands in there because it can do that.

00:19:43.324 --> 00:19:47.304
It can, of course,
also run SSH commands to connect

00:19:47.364 --> 00:19:50.424
to some remote machine
and run commands there.

00:19:50.504 --> 00:19:53.444
So that would be an alternative way of
solving this problem.

00:19:53.524 --> 00:19:57.404
And therefore,
using such a virtual machine

00:19:57.424 --> 00:20:01.354
serious security step-up. But
if there's one main takeaway from this

00:20:01.524 --> 00:20:05.484
it's that you should at least take this
first step because that's super easy.

00:20:05.524 --> 00:20:09.184
It's just a bunch of config files you need
to edit, and that you should at

00:20:09.344 --> 00:20:11.664
least also hide and encrypt your secrets.

00:20:11.924 --> 00:20:15.523
If you do that,
you're already so much more secure than

00:20:16.204 --> 00:20:20.104
And therefore,
with those steps implemented,

00:20:20.244 --> 00:20:23.874
100% guarantee that things can't go wrong,
but it's

00:20:23.904 --> 00:20:26.484
way,
way more than you probably have right now.

00:20:26.774 --> 00:20:30.604
And the next time you see a video by me
or someone else about a big

00:20:30.784 --> 00:20:34.644
supply chain attack,
